Nvidia Corporation, founded in 1993 by Jensen Huang, Chris Malachowsky, and Curtis Priem, began as a company focused on graphics processing technology. Headquartered in Santa Clara, California, Nvidia launched its first product, the NV1 graphics card, in 1995. The company's major breakthrough came in 1999 with the introduction of the GeForce 256, considered the first graphics processing unit (GPU), revolutionizing personal computer graphics and gaming.

Throughout the 2000s, Nvidia expanded its influence in the gaming industry, acquiring rival 3dfx in 2000 and consistently releasing powerful GPUs under the GeForce brand. In 2006, Nvidia introduced CUDA, a parallel computing platform that allowed developers to use GPUs for tasks beyond graphics, such as scientific computing and artificial intelligence.

In the 2010s, Nvidia pivoted further into AI, data center solutions, and autonomous driving technologies. Its GPUs became essential for training deep learning models, underpinning modern breakthroughs in AI and machine learning. The company also launched its Tegra processors, which powered devices like the Nintendo Switch.

Nvidia continued to grow through strategic acquisitions, including Mellanox Technologies in 2020, strengthening its data center offerings. In 2022, a proposed acquisition of chip designer Arm was abandoned due to regulatory hurdles.

As of the 2020s, Nvidia is a leader in graphics technology, AI computing, and high-performance computing, playing a central role in driving innovations across industries, from gaming and entertainment to scientific research and autonomous vehicles.

claude
